04040nam a22005535i 9780822394747DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223947477 a10.1515/97808223947472doi  a(DE-B1597)553236  a(OCoLC)1082918099  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1992.55 7aPER0100302bisacsh1 aFuqua, Joy V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrescription TV :bTherapeutic Discourse in the Hospital and at Home /cJoy V. Fuqua. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b15 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION Television, Hospital, Home -- t1. Convalescent Companions: Hospital Entertainment before Television -- t2. Television Goes to the Modern Hospital -- t3. Positioning the Patient: The Spatial Therapeutics of Hospital Television -- t4. Television in and out of the Hospital: Broadcasting Directly to the Consumer-Patient -- t5. Mediated Agency: Consumer-Patients and Pfizer's Viagra Commercials -- tCONCLUSION Our Bodies, Our (tv) Selves -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTracing the history of television as a therapeutic device, Joy V. Fuqua describes how TVs came to make hospitals seem more like home and, later, "medicalized" the modern home. She examines the introduction of television into the private hospital room in the late 1940s and 1950s and then moves forward several decades to consider the direct-to-consumer prescription drug commercials legalized in 1997. Fuqua explains how, as hospital administrators and designers sought ways of making the hospital a more inviting, personalized space, TV sets came to figure in the architecture and layout of health care facilities. Television manufacturers seized on the idea of therapeutic TV, specifying in their promotional materials how TVs should be used in the hospital and positioned in relation to the viewer. With the debut of direct-to-consumer prescription drug advertising in the late 1990s, television assumed a much larger role in the medical marketplace. Taking a case-study approach, Fuqua uses her analysis of an ad campaign promoting Pfizer's Viagra to illustrate how television, and later the Internet, turned the modern home into a clearinghouse for medical information, redefined and redistributed medical expertise and authority, and, in the process, created the contemporary consumer-patient.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHospital patientsxServices for. 0aPatientsxServices for. 0aTelevision broadcastingxHealth aspects. 0aTelevision in medicine. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822394747zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822394747423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822394747.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles